TRIP COMMENTS: Central Valley Bird Symposium field trip to Western Amador County.  Route started at East Liberty Road, north on Curran Road with a stop at Camanche Hills Hunting Preserve to Camanche Parkway, east on Jackson Valley Road to Lake Amador/Buena Vista Trout Farm, back to Martin Lane and north to Highway 88. We headed west on Highway 88 to Jackson Valley Road/Dave Brubeck Lane to the Ione WTP.  The route continued north on Five Mile Drive to Highway 104/Twin Cities Road and onto the Sacramento County line. We then headed back east to Michigan Bar Road to Carbondale Road, with a stop at the gravel pit pond near Maxwell Road. At Highway 16 we turned east to Highway 49 then south to Vaira Ranch Road  and onto Tonzi Road where we took a lunch break. Following a bathroom break in Ione we drove back back down Highway 124 to Sutter Creek-Ione Road and Goffinet Reservoir and the small pond 2 miles further east.  Finally we headed back on 124 and Highway 88 west  to the  Amador County - San Joaquin county line and back to Stockton. Weather was clear with only a slight breeze - temperatures ranged from the high 40s to the high 60s. Most of the counts are conservative estimates for the day (unless under 5) since I didn't focus on the numbers during this trip.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Viewed at the Ione WTP

For the Honey Lake CBC, Jon Dunn and I covered the Dakin Unit of the Honey Lake NWR along with the Honey Lake Ranch area to the west.  All distances are measured as one way as per eBird protocol.  About 5 hours was devoted to driving and walking areas of the Dakin Unit and the remaining time was spent birding our way to the Honey Lake Ranch off Hemphill Road where we birded on foot for about 2 hours.  The weather was challenging with ice fog persisting all day.  Temperatures ranged from 17 F at the start to a high of 26 F.  The entire day was relatively calm. Nearly all water was frozen except for one small pond that had water being pumped into it and the area was in the grips of a long drought.

SPECIES COMMENTS: These 3 immature Bald Eagles flew in together. Each of them had the distinctive large size of an eagle. Long, rectangular, straight wings, with a head equal in size or proportion to the tail, unlike Golden Eagles, who look like someone grabbed them by the tail, and pulled the head into the body. These 3 Bald Eagles were in various stages of having diffuse white on the head, body, and tail, demonstrating various ages.

TRIP COMMENTS: Tom Edell, Richard Norton, and I spent an extended period of time along the northeastern shore of Lake Crowley in search of several birds that had been reported the previous day.  We worked along the eastern shoreline of the lake from the west end of Layton Springs Road north to the delta scanning the ducks, ibis, shorebirds, and gulls (1:10-2:50 pm).  I did my best to count most of the species seen, but I did not do so for ducks or coots given the large numbers and the fact that most were quite distant.  We saw a few sparrows and thrashers while driving north along a track through the sagebrush scrub, but we did not spend much time looking for land birds during our visit.  After checking the delta, we returned almost ot Benton Crossing Road and then took another track to the southwest by a small spring and out toward the lakeshore, which we scoped briefly and from a moderate distance (ca. 3:10-3:25 pm).  There were more pelicans and gulls here, in addition to a few shorebirds and ibis, but nothing of sufficient interest for us to walk the 200 meters or so to the shoreline.  It was mostly clear, but with a few clouds over the mountains, a mild (<5 knot) breeze from the southwest that seemed to increase to 5+ knots during our visit, and temperatures increasing from 79 F to 81 F during our visit (based on the thermometer in Tom's vehicle).  1:10-3:25 pm.--After checking the northeastern shore, we drove back west along Benton Crossing Road and then south though the scrub out the peninsula.  We saw many more Eared Grebes, good numbers of Western Grebes, California Gulls, and American White Pelicans, quite a few Bank Swallows and a few swallows of other species, one Clark's Grebe and one immature male Northern Harrier, two flocks of 30-40 Red-winged Blackbirds, and a few additional shorebirds at a great distance.  We also saw a Coyote along Benton Crossing Road near the crossing over the Owens River.----Mule Deer - 1.

John Luther spent the night here and we started birding from the kitchen window about 7:15 a.m. as we at breakfast.  Both Slate-colored Fox Sparrows, five Lark Sparrows and at least on Lincoln's were among the regular birds that visited the feeders.  When we finally headed out the door, there was frost on the lawn so still about 35F, no wind and clear sky.  We headed over to the pond overlook and did find the Townsend's Solitaire (10 days now) and also an adult Bald Eagle.  We also got to see the Bald Eagle fly downriver and later back up again.----We walked down to the Gristmill gravel bar overlook, picking up the Barrow's Goldeneye, but no Acorn Woodpeckers.  We ran into Jim Pompy at the Killdeer Island overlook and he spotted the American Kestrel while John was first to spot the male Northern Harrier.  The latter may be the one that stayed and nested across from my home last year.

Susan Peterson, Laurie Dann and I arrived about 6:45 a.m. on this cold (~44F), partly cloudy morning with strong winds, which created enough wind chill for gloves and knit caps.  We met Robert Snow and my co-leader Mary Schiedt at the tall tower in hopes of finding the Peregrine Falcon that often perches there, but to no avail.  We then drove to the Visitor Center's parking lot and began scoping the birds in the ponds of Lost Slough.  From here we moved up to the next parking lot.  The Virginia Rail only called a few times but never let us see it.  Jim Pompy got a late start from Sacramento, but that turned out to be a lucky break because on his way to meet us, he spotted an adult Bald Eagle perched on a berm in ponds opposite the Barn.  Zooming over we were able to all see it before it took off.  We checked the ponds in this area and then drove to the RR crossing to scope the northern ponds of Lost Slough from this elevated area.  Waterfowl, shorebirds and fantastic Sandhill Cranes were seen from all these areas.   ----Finally it was time to try birding the trail that begins at the Visitor Center and goes to "The Point".  Due to high winds, the passerines were scarce and we really had to work for them, except for Golden-crowned Kinglets that were seen at three locations and were very cooperative, coming within three feet of me several times.  We returned for lunch at the Visitor Center picnic tables where Jim spotted a wonderful Townsend's Warbler as we ate our sandwiches.  ----Before heading back to Stockton we briefly checked the ponds and mud for any new birds that might have flown in and made a quick side trip to the airstrip up by the prison to see if Burrowing Owls were visible...they were not.----Considering the strong winds we battled all day, our list of 79 species is very good.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This adult was found by Jim Pompy and still there perched on a berm opposite The Barn for all of us to see.  It flew away before we could get out of our two vehicles.

I first spotted eagle yesterday, Jan 26 2013. So I returned today to see if the bald eagle was still present and if so attempt to obtain photos. Fortunately, the eagle was still at the location today. Upon further viewing and inspection of photos ( a couple linked here), I believe that the bird is a juvenile because of the lack of white on the back and belly.

Large eagle observed perched and flying. Large size confirmed in flight when compared to several species; slightly smaller than white pelicans, approximately twice the size of osprey and great egret. When flying and viewing the eagle's underside there was extensive white from axilla to base of primaries. In addition, the tail was mostly white with dark tips. When perched I had a good view and observed: large hooked bill that was dark at tip and yellow at base; the lores were light; the top of the head was dark but the cheek and the throat were mostly  white; the primaries were very dark; the other flight feathers were lighter brown; about half of the wing coverts had pale tips. Based on the plumage, this bird was immature probably  a 2nd year bird.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Presumably a third year bird found at the south end of the lake (seen earlier near the boat launch by another birder in our party). This was a rather large and bulky raptor with a short tail and broad wings. Head appeared large with large and obvious mostly yellow bill (dark at tip). The head and neck were mostly white but still with some dark brown mottling especailly behind the eye.  Body and wings of the bird dark brown overall with moderate white mottling. The white in the underwing was concentrated on the underwing coverts and present but limited on the flight feathers themselves with not distinct patterning. Tail was mostly dirty white with dark brown especially concentrated on feather edges and tips creating an indistinct dark terminal band. Feet yellow. Upper surface of bird not seen.

Birding only in front of the "No Birding" signs. The winds were calm early and visibility was very good so we were able to scope the three oxidation ponds fairly well for ducks and geese. The result is that we were able to survey all the major ponds except for the southeast portion of storage pond #1. Other than Aleutian Cackling Geese, all the geese were flyovers. All the flyover white geese were Snow Geese except for a very large flock of Ross's Geese. Birding with John Harris and Sal Salerno.

Paul Lehman and I were joined by Louis Bevier, Larry Ballard, and Joel Barrett in search of a Zone-tailed Hawk that had been seen the last few days over the ridges north of the northeastern arm of the lake.  We therefore began scanning the skies along Santa Ana Road and, within two minutes of our arrival, Paul spotted the hawk flying west.  After losing this bird before I was able to get a satisfactory view, Paul managed to relocate the hawk flying back-and-forth along a ridge just west of the park entrance.  We then spent an extended period of time studying the hawk at a moderate distance before seeing it drop down into the trees.  In the hope of seeing this bird perched, we entered the park and checked the hillside where it disappeared.  Unfortunately, the hawk was flushed moments after we spotted it and then disappeared for a short while before Paul again relocated it circling overhead.  Although our efforts were concentrated on the hawk, we did pay at least some attention to the other birds present and, before leaving the area, we also checked the marina, where an Eastern Phoebe had been seen a month or so earlier.  It was clear, with no more than a trace (<5 knot) breeze, and temperatures that increased from the upper 50s to the upper 60s during our visit.  10:15 am - 12:30 pm.----California Ground-Squirrel - 10 (I saw at least ten squirrels, but there were probably many more than this).
